In my use case, I was downloading a large file from an nginx powered server, and processing the data on the fly. To do that, I read small bits of data from the inputstream corresponding to what is currently being processed, and took my time processing before consuming more data. Somehow, the system (or maybe OkHttp), cached a large piece of the file ahead of time, and wouldn&#39;t contact the server for more unless I consumed this cache. This was  evident because even after turning the server off, the program would be able to continue reading and processing for a few minutes before the unexpected end of stream is reached.

Turns out, nginx is configured to [drop the connection if the client didn&#39;t contact the server for 60s by default][1]:

&gt;     Syntax: 	send_timeout time;  
&gt;     Default: 	send_timeout 60s;  
&gt;     Context:	http, server, location
&gt; Sets a timeout for transmitting a response to the client. The timeout is set only between two successive write operations, not for the transmission of the whole response. If the client does not receive anything within this time, the connection is closed. 

So, the dilly-dallying while consuming the data caused the issue. I solved the issue by increasing the timeout in my server configuration:

    location /MyLargeDownloadsFolder/ {
       send_timeout 600s;
    }

  [1]: https://nginx.org/en/docs/http/ngx_http_core_module.html#send_timeout

